"'''Interlude at Darkknell'''" is a four-part novella coauthored by [[Timothy Zahn]] and [[Michael A. Stackpole]], parts one and four written by Zahn and part two, part three, and the epilogue by Stackpole. It was published in the compilation of short stories ''[[Tales from the New Republic]]'' by [[Bantam Spectra]] in December 1999. It was also included in a Czech-language anthology ''[[Setkání v mlze]]'' in July 2009.

==Plot summary==
The novella pits [[Senator/Legends|Senator]] [[Garm Bel Iblis/Legends|Garm Bel Iblis]], who is believed to have died along with his family at the hands of an [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] assassin, and [[Corellian Security Force|CorSec]] inspector [[Hal Horn]] against one of the Empire's most dangerous agents—namely, [[Ysanne Isard]]. [[Moranda Savich]], hiding from Inspector Horn, acquires a pack of [[Datacard/Legends|datacards]] that include sensitive Imperial information. Isard, with her cohorts, seeks to retrieve the datacards at the behest of [[Armand Isard/Legends|Armand Isard]].

==Continuity==
According to the ''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'', the events of ''Interlude at Darkknell'' take place in about [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]]. However, this contradicts events described in ''[[Star Wars: The Force Unleashed]]'', in which Garm Bel Iblis is [[Battle on Death Star I|taken to the Death Star]] by [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]]. ''Interlude at Darkknell'', which describes Bel Iblis as being only vaguely aware of "Tarkin's project", consequently cannot have taken place later than [[2 BBY/Legends|2 BBY]].

The description of explosion of the [[Treitamma Political Center]] killing Bel Iblis' family also contradicts older accounts of them being "rounded up and arrested" and ultimately "executed" by Imperial soldiers, as stated in ''[[The Thrawn Trilogy Sourcebook]]''. Similarly, ''[[The Essential Guide to Characters]]'' reports that the "Corellian and his wife and children were rounded up on the planet of Anchoron and arrested. Imperial soldiers executed his family, forcing Garm to watch."

